{"type":"message","id":"f5a97ed4","parentId":"35a088c0","timestamp":"2026-05-07T05:18:30.089Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"I see the session is being steered. Let me check if there's a pending run result. The session status was \"failed\" before. Let me check if the session is now running properly after the steer.\n\nActually, looking at the conversation flow, I think the problem is that this main session (agent:main:main) is the one being used by the Telegram session. But the Telegram session uses model \"gpt-5.4-mini\" and is \"failed\". When I sent a sessions_send, it seems it routed to the main session (agent:main:main) not the Telegram session.\n\nWait, let me re-read. The sessions_history shows messages from agent:main:main session, but the content says it's routing from \"agent:main:telegram:default:direct:1060942816\" via sessions_send. \n\nSo the routing is: I used sessions_send on this main session, but it's pointing back to the same Telegram session that failed. The real issue is that the Telegram user is on session \"agent:main:telegram:default:direct:1060942816\" which ran gpt-5.4-mini and failed because there's no OpenAI API key, and that's the conversation they were using.\n\nI switched to minimax/MiniMax-M2.7, but the steer command I sent might have triggered a new run with the new model. Let me check if that run completed successfully by looking at the session history again, or maybe the steer caused the Telegram session to retry with MiniMax-M2.7 instead of failing again.\n\nThe steer command returned \"accepted\" status, so it should process now. I should let the human know what I found—the gpt-5.4-mini model was failing due to missing OpenAI credentials, and I've already initiated a switch to MiniMax-M2.7 to resolve it. Let me also verify that MiniMax-M2.7 actually has the required API key configured, since the session status shows it does.\n","thinkingSignature":"e5ef8d7b7e562ad7d65344aca7fc620e5d794e1